who again was a patron of Yājñavalkya, 
a pupil of Āruṇi. But this difficulty is 
not fatal. 11) Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa, xi. 5, 3, 2; 
Kauṣītaki Upaniṣad, i. 1. 12) i. 1, 2, 11; ii. 2, 1, 34; iii. 3, 4, 19; 
iv. 4, 8, 9; xi. 2, 6, 12. 13) iii. 5, 1. 14) iii. 11, 4; v. 11, 2; 17, 1; vi. 
8, 1. 15) viii. 7. 16) xxvi. 4. 17) i. 6. 18) i. 1 et seq. 19) Vedische Studien, 3, 146. 20) Indian Literature, 69. But cf. xxiii. 
1, 5. 21) vii. 8. Cf. viii. 6. 22) i. 42, 1. 23) vii. 2, 2, 1 (a late passage). 24) iii. 11, 8, 1 et seq. 25) On Taittirīya Brāhmaṇa, loc. cit. 
