Brāhmaṇa, vi. 7, 2, 8.

द्रोणाहाव
द्रोणाहाव
 is used as an epithet of Avata, ‘well,’ in the 
Rigveda,
	1 apparently in the sense of ‘having wooden buckets’ 
with reference to the drawing up of water. 1) x. 101, 7. Cf. Zimmer, Altindisches Leben, 157.

द्वादश
द्वादश,
 ‘consisting of twelve,’
	1 is used of the year in the 
Rigveda (vii. 103, 9). See Nakṣatra. 1) Cf. Oldenberg, Zeitschrift der Deutschen Morgenländischen Gesellschaft, 48, 645 et seq.

द्वापर
द्वापर
 See Akṣa and Yuga.

द्वार्
द्वार्
 is frequently used from the Rigveda
	1 onwards
	2 to 
denote the ‘door’ of a house. The later form, Dvāra, has the 
same sense.
	3 Cf. Gṛha. The ‘door-fastener’ is called Dvāra
pidhāna in the Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa.
	4 1) i. 13, 6. 2) Av. viii. 3, 22; xiv. 1, 63; Vāja
