	4 
‘Grandson’ is also expressed by Pautra (‘son's son’) in the 
Atharvaveda and later,
	5 while the sense of ‘great-grandson’ is 
accurately conveyed as early as the Rigveda
	6 by Pra-ṇapāt, 
used beside Napāt, ‘grandson.’ Naptī, the feminine, is practi
cally limited to the Saṃhitās,
	7 and denotes ‘daughter.’ The 
use in the Veda throws no light on the original use of the 
word.
