the Śatapatha Brāhmaṇa
	3 he is styled Hairaṇyanābha, ‘de
scendant of Hiraṇyanābha,’ and in the Śāṅkhāyana Śrauta 
Sūtra
	4 he is called Para Āhlāra Vaideha, a fact testifying to 
the close connexion of Kosala and Videha. A Yajña-gāthā, 
or ‘sacrificial verse,’ there
	5 cited mentions Hiraṇyanābha 
Kausalya in connexion with Para. 1) Taittīrīya Saṃhitā, v. 6, 5, 3; 
Kāṭhaka Saṃhitā, xxii. 3 (Indische 
Studien, 3, 473). 2) Pañcaviṃśa Brāhmaṇa, xxv. 16, 3; 
