have done most to combat the view of 
the village community in India as a 
land-holding institution, is prepared to 
recognize the family as a land-owning 
unit, considering that the patria potestas 
is a later growth, and not Indian (see, 
e.g., Village Communities in India, 128 
et seq.). Hopkins, India, Old and New, 
218 et seq., adopts a theory which allows 
of individual and joint family owner
ship side by side, the latter being 
apparently the earlier but the decadent 
stage. He expressly considers (p. 222) 
that the son had an indefeasible right to 
prevent the father from alienating the 
hereditary land, which could only be 
parted with by the consent of the village 
if it were a case of joint ownership 
(cf. the verse cited by Jolly, Recht und 
Sitte, 94). But it must be remembered 
that, as is very clearly shown in the 
