accepted. 5) Rv. i. 87, 4; 89, 7; 186, 8; ii. 34, 4; 
iii. 26, 6; v. 42, 15; vii. 40, 3 6) So Sāyaṇa on Rv. i. 87, 4. This 
view is far-fetched, but is supported, 
in so far as the interpretation of Pṛṣatī 
and Aśva is concerned, by such passages 
as v. 55, 6, where the Maruts are said 
to yoke the Pṛṣatīs as aśvān to their 
chariots; but the sense may be ‘horses 
(and) dappled (mares).’ See, however, 
Pischel, Vedische Studien, 1, 226. 7) Wörterbuch, s.v. 8) See Muir, Sanskrit Texts, 5, 152. 9) Sacred Books of the East, 32, 70; 
184. 10) Op. cit., 5, 151, 152. 
Cf. Zimmer, Altindisches Leben, 83.

